<br>
Look over the Mars Direct Plan, by Robert Zubrin.  The entire mission is accomplished with a delta V of about 7km/sec.  3km/sec of it coming from martian generated propellents that do not have to be luggedfrom earth.<br>
<br>
The remainder, the Earth Orbit Insertion and Mars Orbit Insertion, are accomplished using aerobraking in the respective planetary atmospheres.  <br>
<br>
No one has yet found a credable objection to mars direct.  Its safety, economy, flexability and scientific capability simply cannot be matched by any competing solutions.  It is an extremely elegent and well-though out design.  Plus it can be easily updated by the addition of various nuclear propulsion schemes for increased speed and payload capacity.<br>
<br>
Here are some numbers.<br>
<br>
Chemical-based TMI(Trans Mars Injection)<br>
<br>
240 tonnes to LEO(2 Shuttle C stacks, Mars Direct uses a shuttle configuration called Ares with the payload fairing mounted atop the ET), 6-Month Transit, 500 martian surface days, ~50 tons to martian surface.<br>
<br>
Solid Core NTR<br>
<br>
240 tonnes to LEO, 6 month transit, 500 martian surface days, ~100 tones to martian surface.<br>
<br>
or<br>
<br>
120 tonnes to LEO, 6 month transit, 500 martian surface days, ~50 tones to martian surface.<br>
<br>
NEP(probably VASIMR)<br>
<br>
120 tonnes to LEO, 3 month transit, 700 martian surface days, ~100 tones to martian surface(maximum, with slow trajectory, NASA is not really sharing a lot of details probably more like 75-80 for the 3 month trajectory). <br>
 <br>
As you can see.  This is an effective and affordable method to initiate the exploration of Mars now, with or without the use of nuclear propulsion.  The mission hardware would be the same regardless of propulsion, but would be able to accomodate much more scientific gear, or simply accomplish the same mission in one launch of an HLV instead of two, once nuclear was mature enough to incorporate into the mission plan.<br>
<br>
We could start out modest, have men on Mars by, say 2011, with chemical propulsion.  Within a few years, the nuclear propulsion we are working on for promethius would be capable of sending portable drilling rigs and other bulky hardware with the explorers to greately improve their capabilities.  Drilling would enable them to confirm or deny the existance of liquid water below the surface of mars and the potential life that it may support. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 261<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 2:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=810.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What takes to reach Mars with a manned chemical rocket.</span><hr size=1> The biggest problem I have always had with Mars Direct was that it is too austire. First the transit times are very long, exposing the crew to a large radiation risk. The fact that any propulsion stage must be lifted with the components limits their proformance. With a four man crew in an extreamly cramped space for years, psycological problems come into play. The small crew also requires the biologist to double up as the only physician for the crew. Most six man crew layouts provide two biologist/doctors for greater safety. The mass layout does not provide much room for tools/spares on the surface, sure their is a spare hab but many problems can be repaired without too many problems. <br>
<br>
When the plan was written up in 1990 it was created to be the exact oposite of the SEI plan, small and cheep. The plan in modified form (Mars semi-direct) was taken over by NASA in their Design Reference Mission. The ultimate problem I see with both of them is the reliance on chemical rockets for the return trip. Nuclear rockets can also be feuled by indigonous propellants. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 10:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=810.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What takes to reach Mars with a manned chemical rocket.</span><hr size=1> True, nuclear rockets could be fueled by in-situ propellent generation, it might be nice to see some figures showing how this would impact the mission profile.  <br>
<br>
However, I doubt nuclear would have much to offer in this sort of situation.  We are trying to minimize the amount of weight we have to lug out there, not the gross liftoff weight of the ERV.  Nuclear would probably reduce its GLOW, but the dry mass would increase.  This would increase the cost of the mission, since we are shipping it out there dry.<br>
<br>
The reference ERV design, fueled by methane/oxygen has a dry mass of about 20 tons and 96 tons of propellent when it lifts off for earth. Most of the mass allocation in the ERV is to the crew compartment, things like life support and consumables.  These are non-negotiable.  Only about 5 tons is engines and tankage.  <br>
<br>
You would be hard-pressed to work out an NTR thrust stage that would be lighter than that, and can still lift 15 tons of cargo to earth.  Of course, you wouldn't need to take that 6.5 tons of hydrogen feedstock out with you if you were using NTR, you would just use carbon dioxide, or oxygen, whichever has a higher specific impulse, I wouldn't know how to figure out which has more potential.  <br>
<br>
This would allow you about 10 tons to work with.  This is doable with solid core NTR, the most likely candidate for such a mission due to its proven nature.  Any weight savings you made over this number could be added to comfort upgrades to the crew quarters, which would be nice.  However, I wonder if it is worth all the extra trouble.<br>
<br>
One more concern that I have, what is the radiological impact of having the crew sitting less than 15 meters away from an operating NTR? The propellent would probably shield them during the first phase of the burn, but what about as the tanks approach empty?  I don't know, I'm not a nuclear engineer.<br>
<br>
As for the psychological factors and the cramped conditions, all I can say is that only experience will tell.  The only way to find out if humanity has the mental constitution to explore space is to get out there and see.  NASA is fond of doomsday predictions about mental breakdown and hopeless bickering that could destroy the mission, but they don't know any more than we do. <br>
<br>
Their whole thing about studying these factors for decades on the international space sation is a pointless waste of time and money. Honestly, what can we learn from ISS about human factors that we can't learn from no less than 8 prior Russian space stations?  Including on-orbit stays that outlast anything planned for ISS by that were conducted on Mir?<br>
<br>
Its not like humans have never faced cramped, stressful and dangerous conditions before.  What about the pilgrims, who came to American on the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.updateyourself.co.uk/premiershipmodels/listings/214.htm"><br>
Mayflower</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, there were 104 passengers on a ship only 27.4m long?  That must have been a fun six weeks.  What about the polynesians, sailing thousands of miles across the Pacific, in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>canoes</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->? What about allmost 100 years of submarine warfare? What about antarctic bases and expeditions.  What about the vikings in their longboats and the greeks in their galleys.  A greek <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.richeast.org/htwm/Greeks/kapost/ship.html">trireme</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was 120ft long and had a crew of over 200, how's that for cramped? <br>
<br>
It should be pointed out that the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.marssociety.org">mars society</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is carrying out simulated mars expeditions right now, attempting to identiy and address just these sorts of issues, among others. To the best of my knowledge, they have encountered no show stopping difficulties.<br>
<br>
All i'm saying is that this is nothing fundamentaly new to humanity.  Sure, the background might be novel, but the same issues have been dealt with before, and can be dealt with again.<br>
<br>
As for the physician, there is no reason to even take one along.  One of the things astronauts most resent is constant monitering and harrassment from medical persons on the ground.  Imagine how much worse this would be if there was a physician around 24/7.  Naturally, all the crew members would receive extensive training in first aid, to be able to deal with most emergency situations.  If anything more extensive than basic first aid was required, medical experts on the ground could give detailed instructions.  The time lag in communication might be critical in very extreme cases, but If you are unluckey enough to be injured to that extent on mars, during the very first expeditions no less, then you are pretty much screwed anyway.<br>
<br>
Any one of the crew should be qualified to deal with routine illness and minor injury.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=samardza>Samardza</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 7:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=810.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What takes to reach Mars with a manned chemical rocket.</span><hr size=1> As far as crew isolation, I've never seen anyone mention the Fram.  9 men for three years isolated from outside contact. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1046<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 2:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=810.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What takes to reach Mars with a manned chemical rocket.</span><hr size=1> The Fram?  I'm not familiar with that, please elaborate.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 381<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 5:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=810.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mars Direct crew requirements</span><hr size=1> nebobgrenville  <br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The biggest problem I have always had with Mars Direct was that it is too austire. First the transit times are very long, exposing the crew to a large radiation risk....<br>
<br>
Less than other, more traditional approaches, but certainly less than a faster transit. He also assumes that the crew will remain healthy in .38 G the whole time they're gone, which is another thing often overlooked. We have nothing but wishful thinking to base such an assumption on.<br>
Note that the crewed launch has absolutely no launch escape provision. Not even a capsule, nor any provision for orbital rendesvous with a Soyuz or 2 to transfer the crew.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; With a four man crew in an extreamly cramped space for years, psycological problems come into p</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Maybe a problem, maybe not. People have endures worse, even without only ~20 minute delay in real-time communication with home.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The small crew also requires the biologist to double up as the only physician for the crew. Most six man crew layouts provide two biologist/doctors for greater safety.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Not quite. One experienced major trauma surgeon, certainly. One other person is cross-trained as a field surgeon, and the other 2 are cross-trained as advanced EMT/field medics, able to assist either doc, or do emergency surgery in a pinch with help from Earth if needed.<br>
Similarly, there is one whiz mechanic, able to take anything apart &amp; repair &amp; reassemble it blindfolded. There is one expert general mechanic (one of the assist medics, perhaps), able to do anything with help (as there's one 2nd rate surgeon). The other 2 (including the top surgeon/biologist) are fair jackleg mechanics, able to assist the experts, or in a pinch, do anything with help.<br>
1 primary biologist/doc, one primary mechanic/engineer.  The biologist and geologist take precedence over the medic &amp; mechanic, because we're planning on using the scientific training rather than the emergency training. The primary doctor is completely able to serve as such, as is the primary engineer/mechanic, but that's not the main reason why they're there.<br>
 Each one is cross-trained to be a secondary in one other area, and a poor third place in each of the other 2 specializations.<br>
No specialist doctor who can't do anything else, which is needed every day of the mission -a doctor is needed, but only in emergencies. A geologist is needed every day. The doctor &amp; mechanic half of these people make sure the field scientists can do their jobs.<br>
 We pretty much admit that if somebody breaks a leg, the mission is handicapped, with less chance of doing anything needed, because there's one less person, one less specialist able to help out.<br>
 On the planet, nobody goes alone, and each 2 person team has either an expert or 2 well-trained people in any specialization.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The mass layout does not provide much room for tools/spares on the surface, sure their is a spare hab but many problems can be repaired without too many problems.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Not sure what that last sentence means.<br>
 When the crew gets there, there are 2 ERVs, 1 hab, 2 pressurized rovers, 2 unpressurized rovers, 2 nuclearpower plants, 4 suits, etc, etc.<br>
